PARAGRAPH.#text: By Wallace Witkowski and Polya Lesova, MarketWatch U.S. stocks eked out modest gains Wednesday after earnings from Time Warner Inc., Wyndham Worldwide Corp. and others reinforced a theme of steady improvement for consumer companies. The Nasdaq Composite ended lower. The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI) ended a choppy trading day up 7.22 points, or 0.1%, at 13,986.52. It had fallen as much as 66 points during the session. The S&P 500 Index (SPX) ended up 0.83 point, or 0.1%, at 1,512.12. Sectors attractive to investors for defensive qualities such as dividends -- telecoms and utilities -- led the index, followed by consumer discretionary stocks.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Nick Godt U.S. stock futures pointed to a higher open Wednesday, lifted by hopes that a much-awaited summit of European leaders will present a convincing plan to handle the euro zone's debt crisis. Futures on the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 40 points to 11,702 and those on the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index advanced 4.60 points to 1,229.20. Nasdaq 100 futures gained 9.75 points to 2,331.50. Stocks fell sharply on Tuesday, with the DJIA falling 1.7% and the S&P 500 losing 2% as U.S. data and earnings disappointed investors while markets remained shaky given uncertainty over the European Union's plans.

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market Tone: Cautious ahead of Bernanke press conference. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again. On Tuesday, strong earnings from 3M, Ford Motor, Delta Air Lines and UPS helped set a robust tone from the opening bell.The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 115.49 to 12595.37, its highest close since June 5, 2008. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 21.66 to 2847.54, its highest close since Oct. 31, 2007. And the S&P 500 gained 11.99 to 1347.24, its best close since June 17, 2008.On Wednesday, earnings will come from all directions, with energy and aerospace dominating.On the energy front, Baker Hughes, Cabot Oil & Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ENI, Hess Corp. and National Oil Well Varco report. Energy companies have reported strong earnings, boosted by rising oil prices. Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman report on the aerospace side. Lockheed Martin reported solid earnings Tuesday; its shares rose more than 2%.Other notable earnings: Norfolk Southern, Whirlpool, Las Vegas Sands, Akamai, Baidu, Dr. Pepper Snapple, Green Mountain Coffee Roasters, eBay, Credit Suisse, Southern Co., and Barrick Gold. (A fuller list of key earnings due today are down below.)On the economic front, March durable goods orders are expected to show a 2.4% gain, reversing an unexpected decline in February. Also, the Energy Department reports petroleum data mid-morning. Crude oil stocks are expected to rise 1.1 million barrels and gasoline stocks are expected to decline once again. (A complete list of G7 economic reports due on Wednesday is at the end of this post.)The market surge on Tuesday had some chin-scratchers arguing that investors were buying the rumor (Bernanke will be really soft/nice/kind/luvy-duvy) in anticipation of selling that news (the actual statement/press briefing). PARAGRAPH.#text:

operating structure, Patriot American Hospitality said its purchase of
Wyndham Hotel will boost its funds from operations by about 6%, or 30 cents
a share, in 1998.

Headlines.Author: Christina Binkley
Headlines.Headline: Marriott to Buy Renaissance

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Marriott agreed
 to buy Hong
Kong-based Renaissance Hotel Group for $947 million, plus the assumption of
$53.2 million in debt. The pact pushes aside Doubletree, which had penciled
a deal to buy Renaissance in January. Renaissance holders will receive $30
a share from Marriott, more than 10% above Doubletree's pact. Renaissance
will pay Doubletree a $15 million breakup fee.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Marriott to Buy Renaissance
